WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:09.860 align:middle line:90%


00:00:09.860 --> 00:00:12.818 align:middle line:90%
[THEME MUSIC]

00:00:12.818 --> 00:00:24.468 align:middle line:90%


00:00:24.468 --> 00:00:26.260 align:middle line:84%
>>GEORGE NOORY: Welcome
to "Beyond Belief."

00:00:26.260 --> 00:00:28.870 align:middle line:10%
George Noory with you with our
special guest Tom Campbell.

00:00:28.870 --> 00:00:30.740 align:middle line:10%
Now, who is Tom Campbell?

00:00:30.740 --> 00:00:33.700 align:middle line:84%
He's a very serious
explorer of the frontiers

00:00:33.700 --> 00:00:36.640 align:middle line:84%
of reality, the
mind, consciousness,

00:00:36.640 --> 00:00:37.870 align:middle line:90%
and psychic phenomenon.

00:00:37.870 --> 00:00:39.850 align:middle line:84%
He's been doing it for
more than 40 years.

00:00:39.850 --> 00:00:41.590 align:middle line:90%
Tom, welcome to "Beyond Belief."

00:00:41.590 --> 00:00:42.140 align:middle line:84%
>>TOM CAMPBELL:
Thank you, George.

00:00:42.140 --> 00:00:42.960 align:middle line:10%
Glad to be here.

00:00:42.960 --> 00:00:44.668 align:middle line:10%
>>NOORY: 40 years
you've been doing this?

00:00:44.668 --> 00:00:45.820 align:middle line:10%
>>CAMPBELL: 40 years.

00:00:45.820 --> 00:00:47.320 align:middle line:10%
>>NOORY: How did
this start for you?

00:00:47.320 --> 00:00:50.800 align:middle line:10%
>>CAMPBELL: Well, I was
in graduate school working

00:00:50.800 --> 00:00:54.850 align:middle line:10%
on my PhD, and I saw
a notice that said

00:00:54.850 --> 00:00:55.990 align:middle line:10%
learn how to meditate.

00:00:55.990 --> 00:00:59.260 align:middle line:90%
Special for students, $25.

00:00:59.260 --> 00:01:00.370 align:middle line:90%
That's where it started.

00:01:00.370 --> 00:01:04.989 align:middle line:84%
I paid my $25 because I wanted
to get by on less sleep.

00:01:04.989 --> 00:01:08.230 align:middle line:84%
Graduate students tend to
work long hours, particularly

00:01:08.230 --> 00:01:12.160 align:middle line:84%
in experimental physics like
I was in, so that started me.

00:01:12.160 --> 00:01:14.860 align:middle line:84%
And within two
months, I found out

00:01:14.860 --> 00:01:18.820 align:middle line:84%
I could debug my software
in a meditation state

00:01:18.820 --> 00:01:21.610 align:middle line:84%
much faster and much
more effectively than I

00:01:21.610 --> 00:01:23.440 align:middle line:84%
could actually looking
at the printout.

00:01:23.440 --> 00:01:25.600 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: So that
$25 was worth it?

00:01:25.600 --> 00:01:26.890 align:middle line:90%
>>CAMPBELL: It was worth it.

00:01:26.890 --> 00:01:29.800 align:middle line:84%
And it opened up a whole
new reality for me,

00:01:29.800 --> 00:01:31.970 align:middle line:84%
because before, like
most physicists,

00:01:31.970 --> 00:01:36.760 align:middle line:84%
if you can't measure it, it's
not real or it's irrelevant.

00:01:36.760 --> 00:01:39.490 align:middle line:84%
And at that point, that was
nothing I could measure,

00:01:39.490 --> 00:01:43.870 align:middle line:84%
but it was real, because
it was my software that was

00:01:43.870 --> 00:01:46.270 align:middle line:90%
being debugged, and it worked.

00:01:46.270 --> 00:01:48.730 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Did you end up
getting the PhD in physics?

00:01:48.730 --> 00:01:50.740 align:middle line:84%
>>CAMPBELL: I did
not get the PhD.

00:01:50.740 --> 00:01:52.870 align:middle line:90%
I did get a PhD education.

00:01:52.870 --> 00:01:55.390 align:middle line:84%
I finished the thesis
and did all of that,

00:01:55.390 --> 00:01:59.710 align:middle line:84%
but I was needed elsewhere,
and my major professor

00:01:59.710 --> 00:02:02.980 align:middle line:84%
wanted me to do another
paper after the first one.

00:02:02.980 --> 00:02:05.807 align:middle line:84%
So I declined and went
out and started my life.

00:02:05.807 --> 00:02:07.390 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: And as you
started your life,

00:02:07.390 --> 00:02:11.480 align:middle line:84%
you started talking about
investigating consciousness.

00:02:11.480 --> 00:02:12.822 align:middle line:90%
What did you uncover?

00:02:12.822 --> 00:02:14.530 align:middle line:84%
>>CAMPBELL: Well,
actually, what happened

00:02:14.530 --> 00:02:18.490 align:middle line:84%
is that just after I
graduated and took a job,

00:02:18.490 --> 00:02:20.770 align:middle line:90%
I ran into Bob Monroe.

00:02:20.770 --> 00:02:23.020 align:middle line:84%
And Bob Monroe had
just built a building

00:02:23.020 --> 00:02:26.388 align:middle line:84%
for studying consciousness, but
he didn't have any scientists.

00:02:26.388 --> 00:02:28.180 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Expert in
out-of-body experiences.

00:02:28.180 --> 00:02:28.980 align:middle line:90%
>>CAMPBELL: Expert.

00:02:28.980 --> 00:02:32.950 align:middle line:84%
So I agreed to be one of
his scientists for free

00:02:32.950 --> 00:02:35.140 align:middle line:84%
if he would teach
me what he knew.

00:02:35.140 --> 00:02:37.960 align:middle line:84%
So I spent the next
five, six, seven

00:02:37.960 --> 00:02:41.380 align:middle line:84%
years spending as much
as 20 hours a week

00:02:41.380 --> 00:02:43.820 align:middle line:90%
with Bob Monroe in his lab.

00:02:43.820 --> 00:02:47.200 align:middle line:84%
And I was building equipment,
and I was doing experiments

00:02:47.200 --> 00:02:50.560 align:middle line:84%
with other people, but I also
was an experiment myself.

00:02:50.560 --> 00:02:54.940 align:middle line:84%
So Bob taught me how to
go out-of-body on demand,

00:02:54.940 --> 00:02:59.330 align:middle line:84%
and how to make that so stable
that I could do experiments

00:02:59.330 --> 00:03:00.130 align:middle line:90%
there.

00:03:00.130 --> 00:03:01.300 align:middle line:90%
I could do research there.

00:03:01.300 --> 00:03:03.040 align:middle line:84%
Change one variable,
do it again.

00:03:03.040 --> 00:03:04.450 align:middle line:90%
See if you get the same results.

00:03:04.450 --> 00:03:06.525 align:middle line:84%
Change another,
variable do it again.

00:03:06.525 --> 00:03:07.330 align:middle line:90%
And so on.

00:03:07.330 --> 00:03:12.250 align:middle line:84%
And doing that for
about 35 years,

00:03:12.250 --> 00:03:15.010 align:middle line:84%
I thought I understood
how it worked.

00:03:15.010 --> 00:03:18.400 align:middle line:84%
So then I wrote a book
about consciousness.

00:03:18.400 --> 00:03:20.650 align:middle line:84%
The "My Big Toe" book
has really started out

00:03:20.650 --> 00:03:22.720 align:middle line:90%
as a theory of consciousness.

00:03:22.720 --> 00:03:26.440 align:middle line:84%
And being a physicist, I should
have picked up on it earlier,

00:03:26.440 --> 00:03:28.490 align:middle line:84%
because I knew consciousness
was fundamental,

00:03:28.490 --> 00:03:30.430 align:middle line:84%
short of the things
I learned there.

00:03:30.430 --> 00:03:34.120 align:middle line:84%
But about two years after
I published these books,

00:03:34.120 --> 00:03:38.890 align:middle line:84%
I realized that the same
concepts, the same ideas that

00:03:38.890 --> 00:03:43.450 align:middle line:84%
explained consciousness also
explained quantum mechanics,

00:03:43.450 --> 00:03:47.830 align:middle line:84%
and that I could actually
derive quantum mechanics

00:03:47.830 --> 00:03:49.810 align:middle line:90%
from consciousness theory.

00:03:49.810 --> 00:03:52.780 align:middle line:84%
And then I thought a little bit,
and I could derive relativity

00:03:52.780 --> 00:03:53.870 align:middle line:90%
as well.

00:03:53.870 --> 00:03:57.812 align:middle line:84%
So I started looking around for
all the paradoxes in physics.

00:03:57.812 --> 00:03:59.020 align:middle line:90%
Things that weren't answered.

00:03:59.020 --> 00:04:01.255 align:middle line:84%
Things that we know are
true because of experiments.

00:04:01.255 --> 00:04:02.963 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: But they were
all tied together.

00:04:02.963 --> 00:04:04.180 align:middle line:90%
>>CAMPBELL: We had no idea.

00:04:04.180 --> 00:04:06.520 align:middle line:84%
So I could understand
all of those paradoxes

00:04:06.520 --> 00:04:07.850 align:middle line:90%
with this model.

00:04:07.850 --> 00:04:12.010 align:middle line:84%
So then I started moving in
into the physics as well.

00:04:12.010 --> 00:04:15.220 align:middle line:84%
So it's a model that
describes everything objective

00:04:15.220 --> 00:04:18.640 align:middle line:84%
and everything subjective
at the same time.

00:04:18.640 --> 00:04:20.380 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: When I was
younger, I picked up

00:04:20.380 --> 00:04:23.320 align:middle line:84%
Bob Monroe's book,
"Journeys Out of the Body"

00:04:23.320 --> 00:04:27.340 align:middle line:84%
and was fascinated by his
work with astral projection.

00:04:27.340 --> 00:04:30.020 align:middle line:84%
Are you able to astral
project at will?

00:04:30.020 --> 00:04:30.900 align:middle line:90%
>>CAMPBELL: Sure.

00:04:30.900 --> 00:04:31.090 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:04:31.090 --> 00:04:33.520 align:middle line:84%
I've been able to do
that since probably being

00:04:33.520 --> 00:04:35.645 align:middle line:90%
two years with Bob Monroe.

00:04:35.645 --> 00:04:36.520 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: What a gift.

00:04:36.520 --> 00:04:39.400 align:middle line:84%
>>CAMPBELL: Matter of fact, if
you look at Bob's second book,

00:04:39.400 --> 00:04:44.330 align:middle line:84%
which was "Far Journeys," you
will find physicist TC is one

00:04:44.330 --> 00:04:45.130 align:middle line:90%
of the--

00:04:45.130 --> 00:04:46.130 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: You're the guy.

00:04:46.130 --> 00:04:47.320 align:middle line:90%
>>CAMPBELL: I'm the guy.

00:04:47.320 --> 00:04:48.700 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Interesting.

00:04:48.700 --> 00:04:50.360 align:middle line:90%
Virtual reality.

00:04:50.360 --> 00:04:51.350 align:middle line:90%
What is that?

00:04:51.350 --> 00:04:52.880 align:middle line:84%
Well, give me a
definition of that.

00:04:52.880 --> 00:04:53.680 align:middle line:90%
>>CAMPBELL: OK.

00:04:53.680 --> 00:04:56.230 align:middle line:84%
Virtual reality goes by
a lot of different names,

00:04:56.230 --> 00:05:00.160 align:middle line:84%
and the one that scientists
use is information-based.

00:05:00.160 --> 00:05:02.620 align:middle line:84%
It's an information-based
reality.

00:05:02.620 --> 00:05:06.010 align:middle line:84%
That's the same thing as
saying it's a computed reality.

00:05:06.010 --> 00:05:09.670 align:middle line:84%
That's the same as saying
it's a simulated reality.

00:05:09.670 --> 00:05:12.970 align:middle line:84%
It's a simulation or
a virtual reality.

00:05:12.970 --> 00:05:17.290 align:middle line:84%
In other words, all the things
we see, and feel, and hear,

00:05:17.290 --> 00:05:18.940 align:middle line:90%
and so on, are information.

00:05:18.940 --> 00:05:22.090 align:middle line:84%
And that's not too hard to
understand, because our senses,

00:05:22.090 --> 00:05:25.010 align:middle line:84%
we have five senses, and
they all gather information.

00:05:25.010 --> 00:05:29.570 align:middle line:84%
And our reality is how we
interpret that sense data.

00:05:29.570 --> 00:05:32.820 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: We live in a virtual
reality world, they say.

00:05:32.820 --> 00:05:33.620 align:middle line:90%
>>CAMPBELL: Yes.

00:05:33.620 --> 00:05:36.290 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Is that real,
or is it made up?

00:05:36.290 --> 00:05:37.630 align:middle line:90%
>>CAMPBELL: That's real.

00:05:37.630 --> 00:05:39.260 align:middle line:84%
That we live in
a virtual reality

00:05:39.260 --> 00:05:47.180 align:middle line:84%
is the best metaphor
or the best assumption.

00:05:47.180 --> 00:05:49.580 align:middle line:84%
The best model that we
have now of reality.

00:05:49.580 --> 00:05:50.840 align:middle line:90%
Quantum mechanics.

00:05:50.840 --> 00:05:53.690 align:middle line:84%
And many physicists,
particularly

00:05:53.690 --> 00:05:57.110 align:middle line:84%
the younger physicists
that are coming up today,

00:05:57.110 --> 00:05:59.870 align:middle line:84%
believe that this is an
information-based reality,

00:05:59.870 --> 00:06:03.170 align:middle line:84%
because that's what
quantum physics tells us.

00:06:03.170 --> 00:06:05.330 align:middle line:90%
That's what relativity tells us.

00:06:05.330 --> 00:06:08.700 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Living in a virtual
reality world is interesting.

00:06:08.700 --> 00:06:10.790 align:middle line:84%
But I have always thought
of virtual reality

00:06:10.790 --> 00:06:14.360 align:middle line:84%
as you have goggles on, and
you're looking at a video,

00:06:14.360 --> 00:06:16.320 align:middle line:90%
and you're in the video.

00:06:16.320 --> 00:06:18.590 align:middle line:84%
That's not exactly what
you're talking about, is it?

00:06:18.590 --> 00:06:21.410 align:middle line:90%
>>CAMPBELL: No, but it's close.

00:06:21.410 --> 00:06:24.920 align:middle line:84%
If we talk about a virtual
reality game, people are--

00:06:24.920 --> 00:06:29.120 align:middle line:84%
we play virtual reality like
World of Warcraft or the Sims.

00:06:29.120 --> 00:06:31.670 align:middle line:90%
It's more like that.

00:06:31.670 --> 00:06:34.340 align:middle line:84%
But when you put on
the goggles, you're

00:06:34.340 --> 00:06:37.860 align:middle line:84%
actually a participant
in that virtual reality.

00:06:37.860 --> 00:06:41.690 align:middle line:84%
So now we take two of those
and put them together,

00:06:41.690 --> 00:06:43.670 align:middle line:90%
and we have our physical bodies.

00:06:43.670 --> 00:06:46.610 align:middle line:84%
The physical world is
the virtual reality.

00:06:46.610 --> 00:06:48.830 align:middle line:90%
So our body is the avatar.

00:06:48.830 --> 00:06:50.720 align:middle line:90%
We are consciousness.

00:06:50.720 --> 00:06:54.350 align:middle line:84%
And as consciousness, we're
the player of that avatar.

00:06:54.350 --> 00:06:56.105 align:middle line:90%
We make all the choices.

00:06:56.105 --> 00:06:56.980 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Interesting.

00:06:56.980 --> 00:07:00.950 align:middle line:84%
Gregg Braden, on his Gaia
series "Missing Links,"

00:07:00.950 --> 00:07:03.842 align:middle line:90%
talked about a simulated world.

00:07:03.842 --> 00:07:05.300 align:middle line:10%
>>GREGG BRADEN:
The characteristics

00:07:05.300 --> 00:07:06.970 align:middle line:10%
of a simulated world.

00:07:06.970 --> 00:07:10.460 align:middle line:10%
A simulation has a
place where it begins,

00:07:10.460 --> 00:07:14.180 align:middle line:10%
a definite beginning, and it
has a place where it ends.

00:07:14.180 --> 00:07:18.170 align:middle line:10%
And what happens in between
that beginning and that ending

00:07:18.170 --> 00:07:23.420 align:middle line:10%
is based on a mathematic
algorithm, a rhythm of cycles

00:07:23.420 --> 00:07:26.480 align:middle line:10%
in patterns that repeat
again, and again,

00:07:26.480 --> 00:07:28.670 align:middle line:10%
and again on different scales.

00:07:28.670 --> 00:07:34.100 align:middle line:84%
In a simulation, there are rules
that govern the simulation.

00:07:34.100 --> 00:07:38.390 align:middle line:10%
And the idea is that as the
people in the simulation

00:07:38.390 --> 00:07:40.760 align:middle line:10%
become more familiar
with the environment,

00:07:40.760 --> 00:07:44.180 align:middle line:10%
as they learn those
rules, life gets better.

00:07:44.180 --> 00:07:46.700 align:middle line:90%
They improve with practice.

00:07:46.700 --> 00:07:52.880 align:middle line:84%
In a simulation, users have
access to another reality that

00:07:52.880 --> 00:07:55.580 align:middle line:90%
is not within the simulation.

00:07:55.580 --> 00:07:58.280 align:middle line:10%
In a simulation,
the users always

00:07:58.280 --> 00:08:02.020 align:middle line:10%
have access to an
external reality

00:08:02.020 --> 00:08:04.620 align:middle line:10%
that they can tap
into for guidance

00:08:04.620 --> 00:08:07.670 align:middle line:10%
if they get into trouble or
if they need clarification.

00:08:07.670 --> 00:08:10.810 align:middle line:10%
They always have the
ability to communicate

00:08:10.810 --> 00:08:12.868 align:middle line:10%
beyond the simulation itself.

00:08:12.868 --> 00:08:14.660 align:middle line:10%
That's going to be
really important in just

00:08:14.660 --> 00:08:16.070 align:middle line:10%
a few minutes.

00:08:16.070 --> 00:08:19.520 align:middle line:10%
And in a simulation,
as I've just mentioned,

00:08:19.520 --> 00:08:23.430 align:middle line:10%
the user cannot tell the
simulation from the real world.

00:08:23.430 --> 00:08:24.230 align:middle line:10%
All right?

00:08:24.230 --> 00:08:29.120 align:middle line:10%
So these are the characteristics
of a modern simulation

00:08:29.120 --> 00:08:32.570 align:middle line:10%
as we know it today, as we
use them today typically.

00:08:32.570 --> 00:08:36.380 align:middle line:10%
Now, with this in
mind, let's go back

00:08:36.380 --> 00:08:40.820 align:middle line:10%
and look at what our most
ancient and cherished

00:08:40.820 --> 00:08:44.570 align:middle line:10%
spiritual traditions from a
number of different religions

00:08:44.570 --> 00:08:47.180 align:middle line:10%
tell us about the
world that we live in.

00:08:47.180 --> 00:08:50.000 align:middle line:10%
Is it possible that
thousands of years

00:08:50.000 --> 00:08:53.300 align:middle line:10%
ago, our ancestors were
trying to inform us,

00:08:53.300 --> 00:08:56.810 align:middle line:10%
in a language of their time,
something that they understood

00:08:56.810 --> 00:08:59.750 align:middle line:10%
that we are only
beginning to awaken

00:08:59.750 --> 00:09:02.840 align:middle line:10%
to the possibility of
happening in our lives?

00:09:02.840 --> 00:09:05.840 align:middle line:10%
That we are actually
in an artificial world,

00:09:05.840 --> 00:09:08.600 align:middle line:10%
a temporary world, that
has a beginning and an end.

00:09:08.600 --> 00:09:10.430 align:middle line:84%
That we're learning
something here,

00:09:10.430 --> 00:09:14.630 align:middle line:84%
and that we have access to
an external guidance when

00:09:14.630 --> 00:09:16.335 align:middle line:90%
we need that access.

00:09:16.335 --> 00:09:17.710 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: It's kind
of scary, Tom,

00:09:17.710 --> 00:09:20.780 align:middle line:84%
thinking that we live in
a virtual reality world.

00:09:20.780 --> 00:09:21.650 align:middle line:90%
To me it is.

00:09:21.650 --> 00:09:22.940 align:middle line:90%
To you probably not.

00:09:22.940 --> 00:09:23.740 align:middle line:90%
>>CAMPBELL: No.

00:09:23.740 --> 00:09:25.448 align:middle line:84%
What do you find scary
about it, George?

00:09:25.448 --> 00:09:26.990 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Well, it's
just the unknown.

00:09:26.990 --> 00:09:30.110 align:middle line:84%
The fact that it may not
be as real as we think.

00:09:30.110 --> 00:09:33.340 align:middle line:84%
Or if it is real, it's
not what I expected.

00:09:33.340 --> 00:09:35.840 align:middle line:10%
>>CAMPBELL: Well, that brings
us to the definition of what's

00:09:35.840 --> 00:09:39.080 align:middle line:10%
real, and I would say
that there is nothing

00:09:39.080 --> 00:09:41.580 align:middle line:10%
more real than information.

00:09:41.580 --> 00:09:44.010 align:middle line:84%
Information is as
real as it gets.

00:09:44.010 --> 00:09:46.560 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: I mean, are we really
here together right now,

00:09:46.560 --> 00:09:49.600 align:middle line:84%
or is that just a figment
of somebody's imagination?

00:09:49.600 --> 00:09:51.650 align:middle line:90%
>>CAMPBELL: No, we are here now.

00:09:51.650 --> 00:09:53.630 align:middle line:84%
It's not a figment of
somebody's imagination.

00:09:53.630 --> 00:09:58.070 align:middle line:84%
Virtual reality is--
it's not a fake reality.

00:09:58.070 --> 00:09:59.453 align:middle line:90%
It's reality.

00:09:59.453 --> 00:10:01.370 align:middle line:84%
It's not like there's
the virtual reality then

00:10:01.370 --> 00:10:02.840 align:middle line:90%
there's the real reality.

00:10:02.840 --> 00:10:04.930 align:middle line:84%
But that thing
that we just heard,

00:10:04.930 --> 00:10:06.680 align:middle line:84%
I can put that in a
little different terms

